referring to the ability of a bacterium to retain crystal violet dye when washed with an organic solvent (such as ethanol) during the Gram staining procedure. organisms who uses an organic substrate in energy metabolism or who uses an organic substrate as an electron donor in phototrophic metabolism

made of two corresponding pieces, two objects matched together

pertaining to endospores. The cytoplasmic membrane and all contents interior to it. referring to the bacterial cell without the cell wall or interior to the cell wall.

An organism which can grow at low temperatures around zero to five degrees Celsius, but has an optimal growth temperature around fifteen to twenty degrees Celsius or higher. An organism which can grow at low temperatures around zero to five degrees Celsius, but has an optimal growth temperature around fifteen to twenty degrees Celsius or higher. \n

note: Pertaining to colony elevation, elevated above the agar surface in a plateau like projection
Motility produced by alternating periods of smooth-swimming and tumbling. Resulting from counter clockwise and clockwise rotation of flagella respectively.
A catabolic, energy yielding process in which either organic or inorganic compounds serve as both primary electron donor and ultimate electron acceptor.

a cell whose length is roughly two or more times greater than its width

the forestomach of a ruminant animal (cattle, deer, sheep, etc.). This is where cellulose digestion occurs.
a non reducing disaccharide composed of glucose and fructose. Molecular formula C12H22O11. Also known by the common name "table sugar".

pertaining to spores. For endospores; a dividing wall which forms near the beginning of spore formation which separates the cell into two protoplasts, the smaller of which is the forespore. For all spores; cross walls which separate adjoining cells in a hyphae.
pertaining to spore orientation, attached to the substrate directly, without the presence of a stalk. Non stalked.

pertaining to colony texture, easily depressed consistency/texture when probed
having the form of a sphere or globular shape, a round body who's surface is equidistant from its center at all points. Normally used to describe an object in three dimensions

note: a differentiated from of a bacterial cell which can be a survival and/or reproductive structure which may also exhibit dormancy. Spores can be produced as a response to environmental stresses and are therefore often resistant to adverse environmental conditions. Subclassifications of spores include: exospores, endospores, myxospores, conidia, arthrospores, and chlamydospores.
spores arranged in a chain, linked to each other end to end.
New Latin spora &  Middle English, from chayne
pertaining to endospores, a lamellate protein structure external to the outer membrane of the forespore, spore coats are rich in cystine. Internal to the exosporium
Neo-Latin, from spora & Middle English, from cote

differentiated from of a bacterial cells which can be a survival and/or reproductive structure which may also exhibit dormancy. Spores can be produced as a response to environmental stresses and are therefore often resistant to adverse environmental conditions. subclassifications of spores include: exospores, endospores, myxospores, conidia, arthrospores, and chlamydospores.
any spore bearing structure or spore bearing hyphal branch. In actinomycetes, spore producing or spore supporting hyphae.
any spore bearing structure or spore bearing hyphal branch. In actinomycetes, spore producing or spore supporting hyphae.
pertaining to colony form morphology, having a colony structure which stretches or expands over an area.
stretching, distributing, or expanding over an area
a mycelium like structure consisting of chains of sequentially sprouting cells

a culture prepared by pushing an inoculated straight wire deep into a solid medium so that the inoculum is spread along the length of the stab site.
Middle English, from stabben & Latin, from cultūra
a water soluble, aromatic compound, which has color and can bind to other materials in order to impart color.
the process of imparting color, opacity, electron density, contrast, or the ability to fluoresce to a specimen. Commonly combined with microscopy afterward.
pertaining to myxobacterales, the supportive part of the fruiting body. (that holds it above the substrate)

A carbohydrate consisting of many glucose units bound by glycosidic bonds. This polysaccharide is the main energy store of higher plants (and some algae) and is the most common carbohydrate in human diets. Starch consists of amylose and amylopectin.

the third of four main phases of growth that a bacterial population undergoes in a closed system (e.g. batch culture). Occurs directly after exponential phase. The growth curve exhibits a plateau as the growth rate declines and eventually reaches zero.

an organism or population which is distinguishable from at least some of the other populations within a named taxon or category of organisms. The members or cells within a strain are generally considered to be genetically similar or identical and are descended from a pure culture or common ancestor.
a culture prepared by inoculating medium from existing culture. Not a primary culture.
pertaining to sporangium shape, having a sporangium which is not perfectly spherical or globose. Often a polysporous arrangement, where spores are arranged in a clump.
covered completely in a medium. Inundated and enveloped

pertaining to distribution about the cell, located at or positioned near the ends or poles of the cell but not exactly at the poles. (for a rod shaped bacterium subpolar would refer to the area near the short round ends of the cell but not exactly at them.)
the surface or material on which an organism grows and/or attaches. e.g. agar

a mycelium which occurs on the surface of the medium (it may penetrate the medium as well). Also known as a primary mycelium because a substrate mycelium will typically develop before an aerial mycelium. Hydrophilic in nature

pertaining to distribution about the cell, located at or positioned near the ends or poles of the cell but not exactly at the poles. (for a rod shaped bacterium subpolar would refer to the area near the short round ends of the cell but not exactly at them.)

adverb of subterminal. Pertaining to distribution about the cell, located at or positioned near the ends or poles of the cell but not exactly at the poles. (for a rod shaped bacterium subpolar would refer to the area near the short round ends of the cell but not exactly at them.)
a non-reducing disaccharide composed of glucose and fructose. Molecular formula C12H22O11. Also known by the common name "table sugar".

nutritional situation in which two or more organisms combine their metabolic capabilities to catabolize a substance not capable of being catabolized by either one alone. In other words, growth may depend on co-existence.
gradually decreasing in thickness, diameter, width, or size. becoming leaner at one end.

pertaining to or occurring as four spores.

a vegetative yet undifferentiated form of an organism

An organism who, for a time, can survive high temperature conditions that would normally kill other vegetative microorganisms. Potentially capable of surviving pasteurization. Synonymous to "thermotolerant".
Heat loving organism. An organism whose optimal growth temperature is between forty five and eighty degrees Celsius. Compare to "thermoduric".
pertaining to an optimal growth temperature greater than forty five degrees Celsius.
heat loving organism. an organism whose optimum growth temperature is greater than forty five degrees Celsius.
an organism who, for a time, can survive temperature conditions that would normally kill other vegetative microorganisms.
the top or end, usually pointed or slender.
the top or end, usually pointed or slender.
pertaining to colony opacity, allowing the passage of some light but diffusing it as well. Moderately see-through. Semitransparent.
Pertaining to colony opacity, see-through. allowing the passage of light.
pertaining to or occurring as three spores.
pertaining to spore ornamentation, a spore surface which has numerous small dot shaped bumps, which are smaller and more numerous than a warty spore's bumps.
pertaining to sporangium shape, having a sporangium resembling a long narrow tube shape. Often an oligosporous arrangement, where spores are linked in a long curving chain.
pertaining to flagellar motility. A period in random walk motility which results in a random change in cell orientation caused by clockwise rotation of flagella.
pertaining to non-flagellar motility. A jerky form of motility exhibited by bacteria with polar fimbria. Occurs in both flagellate and non flagellate bacteria. Exact mechanism remains unknown.
pertaining to colony elevation, possessing and knob-like protrusion or swelling in the center of the colony.
possessing no offshoots or limbs from the main axis of growth.
pertaining to colony edge morphology, having wave like margins

pertaining to distribution about the cell, located at consistent and equal intervals about the cell. For example, uniform flagellar distribution would be flagella located at an unvarying length apart from one to the other, about the entire cell surface.
pertaining to actinomycetes. Growth which occurs in contact with the substrate.
pertaining to spore ornamentation, a spore surface which as numerous lumpy knob shaped projections on its surface.
a bacterium of the genus vibrio, a genus of Gram negative bacteria

A curved rod shaped bacterial cell, resembling a crescent or incomplete spiral shape. Vibrio cells can resemble a comma by having one end be wider than the other. Vibrios (p.)  also very in length to width ratio from long and slender curves to short and swollen kidney bean like shapes. Not to be confused with the "bacillus" morphology which comprises straight rod shapes (see bacillus). Not to be confused with Vibrio (representing the taxon).
having a vibrio like shape. Curved with a twist as is an incomplete helix turn.
a curved rod shaped bacterial cell, forming a comma or incomplete spiral
pertaining to colony texture, having a gummy, thick, and sticky consistency/texture when probed

A test used to determine if an organism is able to form acetoin and/or diacetyl in a phosphate buffered glucose peptone medium. The test consists of inoculating phosphate buffered glucose peptone medium and subsequent incubation at 37°C (for 48 hrs) or 30°C (for 5 days). Then α-naphtol and KOH are added and the medium is observed for red coloration (which indicates a positive reaction). Part of the IMViC tests.

pertaining to spore ornamentation, a spore surface which has several large mound like bumps upon its surface. However not to be confused with verrucose spores which have lumpy knob shaped bumps upon their surface.
H2O. A transparent, colorless, ordorless, and tasteless liquid.
great in size and extent from side to side. broad, vast.
pertaining to spore ornamentation, see irregular rugose.
having a shape similar to a zigzag; a series of short sharp turns in progression or course.

A type of electron microscopy in which a specimen is scanned by an electron beam which moves in a zigzag raster; a second electron beam synchronously scans a cathode ray tube with a similar raster. Electrons which are secondarily emitted from the specimen are collected and used to control the intensity of the beam in the CRT. this effect produces a pattern of light corresponding to the surface topography of the specimen.
Microscopy in which an electron beam interacts with a specimen and subsequently contributes (directly or indirectly) to the formation of an image of that specimen.

A type of electron microscopy in which an electron beam passes through the specimen which deflects or scatters some of the electrons, electrons whose paths are slightly deviated by the specimen are focused onto a fluorescent screen to form an image of the specimen.
A type of electron microscopy in which electrons pass through the specimen and the energies of the emergent electrons are measured in an analyzer which then constructs an image of the specimen.
A form of microscopy used for a colourless specimen which absorbs little light and would not be visable by bright-field microscopy.

The most common form of light microscopy. This is usually the method that is meant by the term "microscopy". Microscopy in which light from a lamp is concentrated by a condenser and directed onto a specimen (which is usually examined on a slide which rests on the stage), then a series of lenses forms a magnified image of the specimen. This method results in an image of the specimen seen against a lighter background (hence, bright-field). One drawback of this approach is that translucent specimens are often poorly visible unless stained.

A form of microscopy commonly used for examining objects too small to be seen by bright field microscopy. For low or medium power work, the underside of the condenser is fitted with an opaque disc which only allows peripheral rays to pass through the condenser, thus forming a hollow cone of light whose apex is focused in the plane of the specimen. This specimen scatters the rays, some of which enter the objective and form a bright image of the specimen against a dark background (hence, dark-field). For high power work a special oil immersion is used.

A form of microscopy in which a specimen is treated with fluorochrome (usually) and irradiated with ultraviolet radiation and the light emitted forms the image of the specimen in a manner similar in principle to that in bright field microscopy.

A form of microscopy in which ultraviolet radiation is used for both illumination of the specimen and for formation of an image. The image is recorded on a fluorescent screen or on a photographic plate.
Any form of microscopy in which the illuminating beam is focused on the specimen by the objective. The objective acts simultaneously as the condenser and objective lens.

A type of electron microscopy in which very small specimens are cooled rapidly to very low temperatures without prior dehydration such that the water in the specimen forms a "glass like" solid without undergoing crystallization.
An experimental form of microscopy which will allow the three dimensional observation of biological specimens at the atomic level.

A picture made using a camera. A picture produced by photography. An image which is focused onto film or other light sensitive material and then made permanently visible by chemical treatment or digital storage.

Intracellular enveloped magnetic bodies that are present in magnetotactic bacteria and cause cells to align with lines of magnetic force. This allows magnetotactic bacteria to direct cell motility by magnetic field.
the molecule that undergoes a specific reaction with an enzyme.
pertaining to colony edge morphology, having margins with thread or fiber like projections. In layman's terms; fuzzy in appearance
pertaining to colony texture, having a mucus like and slimy consistency/texture.

A mode of fission in which one cell gives rise to many others. This process may involve repeated binary fission taking place within a common envelope, or nuclear divisions followed by the incorporation of each nucleus in a separate daughter cell.
pertaining to an organism which grows optimally in a microaerobic environment. Organisms which, in nature, normally grow in the presence of small amounts of oxygen.
Greek, from āer & Latin, from tolerant. Greek, from an, āer & bíos
pertaining to an anaerobe which can survive or grow in the presence of oxygen. But at suboptimal rates of growth.
Middle English, from obligat. Greek, from an, āer & bíos
a type of anaerobe which can only (must) grow in the absence of oxygen.
Latin, from strictus. Greek, from an, āer & bíos
Latin, from strictus. Greek, from āer & bíos
Middle English, from obligat. Greek, from āer & bíos
a type of aerobe which can only (must) grow in an environment where oxygen is present at partial pressures similar to those in air.

A common mode of asexual reproduction in microorganisms whereby two (daughter) cells are formed by the growth and division of one cell. Transverse binary fission occurs when a cell divides across it's longitudinal axis. Longitudinal binary fission occurs when a cell divides along its longitudinal axis.
Cell division in which cell growth is followed by septum formation which divides the fully grown cell into two separate cells that are similar or identical (daughter cells).

(Normally pertaining to chromosomal DNA.) The percentage of the total nucleic acid that consists of guanine plus cytosine bases. Calculated as [(guanine+cytosine)/(adenine+thymine+guanine+cytosine)] (in which each base name represents the relative molar amount of that base). Expressed as mol% GC. This value is useful in microbial taxonomy.
A dissymmetry ratio of microbial DNA calculated as [(adenine+thymine)/(guanine+cytosine)] (in which each base name represents the relative molar amount of that base)

Steroid carboxylic acids which are synthesized in the liver to aid in the digestion of fats. The salts and amides of bile acids are useful ingredients in media selective for enteric bacteria as they are inhibitory to many non-enteric bacteria.
The reduction of dinitrogen (N2) to ammonia (NH3) by the enzyme nitrogenase. Biological nitrogen fixation is carried out by some bacteria.
Respiratory metabolism in which nitrate(NO3-) or nitrite (NO2-) acts as terminal electron acceptor, and is sequentially reduced to mainly dinitrogen (N2) and/or nitrous oxide (N2O).
A process by which sewage or industrial wastewater is treated. The process involves introducing a mass of bacteria and protozoa to wastewater and then vigorously aerating the mixture by agitation.
Culture media whose exact chemical composition (including trace substances) is quantitatively known.
Culture media whose exact chemical composition is not known. Also called undefined medium.
The time required for a population to double.
A given strain of organism or a trait in an organism which is characteristic of the majority of naturally occurring members of its kind.
The breakdown of a polymer into smaller units by the addition of water.
The NIH genetic sequence database, an annotated collection of all publicly available DNA sequences.
Pertaining to chemistry, possessing hydrophilic characteristics and generally water soluble.
A designation which indicates a newly proposed genus at the time of its initial publication.
see genus novum. The abbreviation used for "genus novum"
A designation which indicates a newly proposed species at the time of its initial publication.
see species nova. The abbreviation used for "species nova"
The name of a species which has been moved from one genus to another but which has retained the specific epithet.

A method often used when testing antibiotic sensitivity and tolerance. This method consists of inoculating the entire surface of an agar plate with a test organism. Then, several small and absorbent paper discs which are impregnated with different antibiotics are placed on the agar surface. After incubation, the antibiotics diffuse creating a zone of growth inhibition around each disc that contains an antibiotic to which the organism is susceptible.

Any procedure used in order to determine if a given bacterial strain produces a coagulase. One of many methods used is the tube test; which involves incubating the test organism with a suitable plasma and observing for clot formation over time.
A pH indicator which turns from red (at pH 4.4) to yellow (at pH 6.2).
Liquid derived from domestic sewage or industrial sources, which cannot be discarded (untreated) into lakes or streams.

Any one of the 23 monomers that make up proteins. Chemically, amino acids are two carbon carboxylic acids containing an amino group and a characteristic substituent (known as the "R group") on the alpha carbon.

The inherent capability of an organism to produce disease. Sometimes used interchangeably with the term "virulence", however virulence refers more to the severity of disease an organism causes within a host.
A disease causing microorganism. To be more specific, any microorganism which can directly interact with another organism to cause disease in that organism.
A taxonomic infrasubspecific rank which has no official standing in nomenclature. Formerly equivalent to subspecies.
A strain or set of similar strains which may be distinguished from other strains (within a given subspecies) based upon its/their pathogenicity for a specific host.

A polymer which forms a mesh like layer outside the plasma membrane of most bacteria but not archaea, forming a cell wall. Structurally, peptidoglycan is a chain of alternating N-acetylglucosamine and N-acetylmuramic acid residues. Additionally, each N-acetylmuramic acid has a short chain of amino acids attached to it which link to each other forming "cross links" between chains. The exact structure of the cell wall varies amongst bacteria (see Gram-type-positive & Gram-type-negative).

A structure which forms a layer external to the cytoplasmic membrane which is responsible for the shape of the cell and protects it from mechanical and osmotic damage. Cell walls occur in algae, plants, fungi, archaea, and bacteria. Both the structure and composition of  cell walls vary greatly depending on species. In bacteria, cell walls are composed of peptidoglycan and exist in two distinct types: Gram positive and Gram negative (see Gram-type-positive and Gram-type-negative).

The capability of an organism to produce disease. Sometimes used interchangeably with the term "pathogenicity", however virulence refers more to the severity of disease an organism causes within a host (severity of symptoms).
A microorganism which is adapted to environments with high osmotic pressures. Similar to halophiles.
used to describe a microorganism which is adapted to environments with high osmotic pressures. Similar to a halophilic.
A revived name. A new name that is published and was also previously published prior to 1 January 1980 however not included in an Approved List.
see nomen revictum. The abbreviation used for "nomen revictum"
A viable specimen of a given organism to which a name has been attached and which is regarded as the permanent representative of a given taxon.
A correction or change of text. Used to indicate an alteration in the outline of a taxon.
A name whose application is uncertain. A name which cannot be applied to a specific organism. May be placed on the list of rejected names by the Judicial Commission.

Any name which has been placed on the list of rejected names. This can done for various reasons by the Judicial Commission (see nomen perplexum, nomen confusum, nomen ambiguum, nomen periculosum, nomen dubium).
see nomen rejiciendum. The abbreviation used for "nomen rejiciendum"
see nomen dubium. The abbreviation used for "nomen dubium"

A perplexing name. Two or more epithets in the same genus (or two or more generic names) that are so similar as to cause uncertainty (regardless of words from different sources) can be treated as perplexing names. Such cases are referred to the Judicial Commission.
A name based upon a mixed culture. May be placed on the list of rejected names by the Judicial Commission.
A name which has been used with different meanings. May be placed on the list of rejected names by the Judicial Commission.
A name whose application is likely to lead to accidents endangering health or life or both or of serious economic consequences. May be placed on the list of rejected names by the Judicial Commission.

A name which must be used instead of all earlier synonyms and homonyms and must be retained even though it may contravene rules of the relevant code. Only the Judicial Commission can place names on the list of conserved names.
A taxonomic body concerned with the interpretation and/or amendment of the rules of microbial nomenclature.
see Judicial Commission . The abbreviation used for "Judicial Commission"
an enzyme that hydrolyzes starch or glycogen into sugars (an enzyme that cleaves glucosidic linkages).
enzymes which hydrolyze starch or glycogen into sugars (enzymes that cleave glucosidic linkages).
Used to describe some process done on site or in its original place.
Used to describe some process done in (within the body of) a living organism.
Used to describe some process done outside of a living organism or some process done in a controlled laboratory setting.
Used to describe some process done using a computer. Can also be used to describe a process done via computer simulation.
Any name used to refer to each of two or more different microbial taxa of the same rank based on different types.
Free of all living cells, viable spores, viruses, and subviral agents capable of replication. Devoid of all forms of life.
Any process that can render objects or environments sterile.
A state of being free from potentially harmful microorganisms. Not to be confused with sterile.
Any substance able to kill at least some types of bacteria.
Able to kill at least some types of bacteria.
Able to inhibit the growth and reproduction of at least some types of bacteria.
The abbreviation used for high performance liquid chromatography. See high performance liquid chromatography.

A type of chromatography that employs very high pressures to force a liquid sample through a tightly packed column of minute particles. Because each component of the sample reacts differently with the column, different flow rates through the column occur for each different component. it is this variance that allows comparison and analysis.
The separation of molecules in a mixture by any technique which exploits the differing extents to which the different molecules become distributed between a stationary phase contiguous mobile phase.

A type of chromatography that employs a thin layer on a flat glass support (often a glass plate with a silica gel layer). First, the substance being tested is applied to one end of the plate. Then, one end of the plate is placed in a solvent (known as the "mobile phase") and over time that solvent rises up the thin layer by capillary action. This process carries the substances being tested with it. As each different substance is drawn up at a different rate, separation occurs and analysis is possible.
The abbreviation used for thin layer chromatography. See thin layer chromatography.
The abbreviation used for polymerase chain reaction. See polymerase chain reaction.

A method for replicating specific sequences of DNA which is capable of forming millions of copies in hours. First, sample dsDNA is denatured (at ~95°C); then primers bind (at ~45°C) to each strand such that 5' to 3' extension of primers will copy the target region. Finally, elongation of strands occurs at around 72°C (this temperature depends on which thermostable polymerase is used) . this cycle is repeated several times as needed.
any enzyme which hydrolyzes peptide bonds in proteins and peptides.
Collagen which has been partially hydrolyzed (normally obtained by boiling).

The main structural protein component of bone, cartilage, and other connective tissues in animals. Structurally, collagen is a microfibrillar protein that consists of three polypeptide chains (each chain being composed of a repeating sequence of three amino acids).
A collagen degrading enzyme or enzyme that breaks down the peptide bonds of collagen. The production of collagenase is a virulence factor in bacteria.
Properties that enable a microorganism to replicate and disseminate within a host and enhance its potential to cause disease.
An organic compound ((NH2)2CO). In animals, urea plays a key role in the metabolism of nitrogenous compounds and is the main nitrogen containing compound in the urine of mammals.
An enzyme which hydrolyses urea into ammonia and CO2.

Deoxyribonucleic acid. A nucleic acid consisting of deoxyribonucleotides that serves as the repository of genetic information in all cells and some viruses. Structurally, DNA consists of a long repeating chain of deoxyribonucleotides (a strand). However, DNA is often double stranded meaning that two strands engage in complementary base pairing with one another. Under physiological conditions the two strands twist around a common axis to form a "double helix".

Ribonucleic acid. A nucleic acid consisting of ribonucleotides that is involved in coding, decoding, regulation, and expression of genes. RNA also plays a key role in protein synthesis and constitutes the genome of some viruses. Structurally, RNA consists of a long repeating chain of ribonucleotides (a strand).
Any enzyme which depolymerizes DNA into mono or oligonucleotide products.
Any enzyme which can cleave the sugar phospahte backbone of a nucleic acid (phosphodiester bonds).
A nuclease that removes nucleotides from one end of a nucleic acid strand sequentially.
A nuclease that cleaves phosphodiester bonds within a nucleic acid strand.
A localized region of tissue which has been damaged physically or altered by any pathological process.
The genetic material of an organism, whether it is encoded in DNA or RNA (as for some viruses) including both genes and non coding regions.
All the genes in a cell or virion.

A small wire bent into a closed loop at one end with a handle at the other. This instrument is used in microbiology for manipulating small quantities of solid or liquid material, particularly for inoculation.
a tool used by microbiologists for retrieving an inoculum. Often simply called a loop.
The matter that settles to the bottom of a liquid.
The enlargement of an organ or tissue owing to an increase in the size of pre-existing cells.
The enlargement of an organ or tissue owing to an increase in the number of cells.
The process of killing cells while preserving their structure and organization in as life like a condition as possible.
Not to be confused with "nitrogen fixation" or "carbon fixation".
characterized as being rich in nutrients, particularly those which support the growth of aerobic photosynthetic organisms (often a term applied to lakes, rivers, ponds, etc.).
characterized as being low in nutrients, particularly those which support the growth of aerobic photosynthetic organisms (often a term applied to lakes, rivers, ponds, etc.).
an apparatus within which objects or materials can be sterilized by subjecting them to high pressure saturated steam at temperatures around 121°C.
from New Latin, bacteria and Greek, phagos
Any virus that can infect and replicate within a bacterial host.
A naturally occurring linear polysaccharide used for storage in certain plants.

Any metal or metalloid of environmental concern (although this definition is not widely accepted). The term "Heavy metals" is often used to refer to metals of high density (Lead, Mercury, Cadmium, etc.) that are toxic to organisms. At higher concentrations, heavy metals may exhibit antimicrobial activity.
The region of soil which containts the root and is directly influenced by root secretions.
made of two corresponding pieces, two objects matched together
A number of similar things occurring together
These terms are often used to refer to cells occurring together. However, these terms can also be used broadly.
The simplest form of carbohydrate. Sugars which are the most basic unit of more complex sugars and therefore, cannot be broken down into simpler sugars by hydrolysis.
A group of carbohydrates that upon hydrolysis yield two monosaccharides. Also, the product which is formed when two monosaccharides undergo a condensation reaction by the removal of water.

ATC Code: J01AA01
CHEBI ID: CHEBI:4392
Drug Bank ID: CHEBI:4392
PubChem ID: CID 54680690
CAS Number: 127-33-3
KEGG DRUG: D03680
InChI Key: FMTDIUIBLCQGJB-SEYHBJAFSA-N
An amino acid which is not found in proteins but is present in the peptidoglycan cross link chains of many Gram negative bacteria.
The abbreviation used for diaminopimelic acid, see diaminopimelic acid.

Linear polymers (polysaccharides) which typically consist mainly of glycerol phosphate or ribitol phosphate linked by phosphodiester bonds. Teichoic acids occur (almost exclusively) in the cell envelope of most gram positive bacteria.

A small lipoprotein which occurs in the outer membrane of some Gram negative bacteria. About one third of outer membrane Braun lipoprotein forms covalent linkages between the outer membrane and the peptidoglycan layer.
the abbreviation used for Braun lipoprotein, see Braun lipoprotein.
synonymous with Braun lipoprotein, use Braun lipoprotein.

An ether of lactic acid and N-acetylglucosamine. One of the two alternating amino sugars which make up the structure of peptidoglycan (alternating units of N-acetylmuramic acid and N-acetylglucosamine). Additionally, lactic acid residues of N-acetylmuramic acid serve as sites of cross linking between adjacent peptidoglycan strands.
an abbreviation used for n-acetylmuramic acid, see n-acetylmuramic acid.
an abbreviation used for n-acetylmuramic acid, see n-acetylmuramic acid.

A monosaccharide derivative of glucosamine. One of the two alternating amino sugars which make up the structure of peptidoglycan (alternating units of N-acetylglucosamine and N-acetylmuramic acid). In fungal cell walls N-acetylglucosamine makes up the polymer chitin.
an abbreviation used for n-acetylglucosamine, see n-acetylglucosamine.
an abbreviation used for n-acetylglucosamine, see n-acetylglucosamine.
A linear polysaccharide composed of repeating units of N-acetylglucosamine. Chitin occurs naturally in fungal cell walls, the shells and exoskeletons of some animals, and others.

Proteins which are synthesized at increased levels in an organism in response to a sudden rise in temperature or an increase in other types of stress (such as UV radiation and high chemical concentration such as ethanol). Many heat shock proteins preform a chaperone function; helping to refold partially denatured proteins. Heat shock proteins also include proteases which help degrade irreversibly damaged proteins.
The abbreviation used for heat shock protein, see heat shock protein.
Latin, from mōlē + -cula & Middle French, equivalent to chape + -eron
A protein that helps fold unfolded proteins or helps refold partially denatured proteins back to an active protein.
A short strand of nucleic acid used to initiate synthesis of a new DNA strand.

The separation of charged particles by means of their dissimilar migration characteristics in a uniform electric field. Various types of electrophoresis separate particles based on charge, size, or binding affinity.

Organized structures which contain or consist of DNA which carry genetic information essential to the cell.  Prokaryotes typically have one a single circular chromosome while eukaryotes typically have several linear chromosomes all located inside a nucleus. The term chromosome is also used to describe the DNA in mitochondria and chloroplasts.

The alteration of a protein's or nucleic acid's shape such that it is no longer biologically active. More specifically, the loss of a macromolecule's secondary, tertiary, and quaternary structure by environmental stress (heat, radiation, strong acid or base, salt concentration, solvents, etc.).
The acquired ability of a microorganism to grow in the presence of an antimicrobial agent that it is usually susceptible to.
The lowest concentration of a given antibiotic which inhibits a given type of microorganism under given conditions.
The abbreviation used for minimum inhibitory concentration, see minimum inhibitory concentration.
The susceptibility of a microorganism to an antimicrobial agent (a microorganism's growth being prevented by the presence of an antimicrobial agent).

Any entity (a single cell, chain of cells, etc.) capable of giving rise to a single colony. Colony forming units per unit volume (or per unit area) is a unit often used to estimate the number of viable cells in a sample.
The abbreviation used for colony forming unit, see colony forming unit.

A film of microorganisms which are usually embedded in self produced extracellular polymers. Biofilm adheres to surfaces, particularly those that are exposed to an aquatic environment. Biofilm typically has slimy characteristics. Examples include dental plaque and algal mats.
The dry weight (or some other estimation) of all organisms in a given habitat.

A vitamin which acts as a cofactor in carboxylation and transcarboxylation reactions acting as a carrier of CO2 in several carboxylase enzymes. Biotin is required as a growth factor for many bacteria.
A linear polymer of beta hydroxybutyrate which occurs in refractile granules within cells of various prokaryotes. See Poly-β-hydroxybutyrate Granules.

A refractile granule which is an accumulation of Poly-β-hydroxybutyrate (PHB). PHB accumulates in various prokaryotes when nutrients other than carbon sources become limiting.  PHB accumulations are then degraded by the cell when carbon sources are limiting,  therefore acting as a reservoir of carbon and/or energy.

Intracellular, membranous, vesicles formed in green sulfur bacteria which act as photosynthetic antenna complexes (light-harvesting complexes). Chlorosomes contain most of the light harvesting pigments involved in photosynthesis.
A type of (often intracellular) storage inclusion which contains sulfur compounds. Sulfur globules are found in a diverse group of sulfur utilizing prokaryotes.
Greek, from glykýs + genēs. Latin, from grānulum
an intracellular inclusion which consists of an accumulation of the storage polysaccharide glycogen.
A multibranched polysaccharide composed of glucose linked together by α glycosidic bonds.
A semi-quantitative, commercial method used to detect enzymatic activities
A serine protease which is found in a diverse set of organisms.
pertaining to sheathed bacteria; a secreted tubular structure formed around a chain of cells or around a bundle of filaments.
pertaining to flagellar sheath; a layer of outer membrane covering the flagellum.

A structure found in both bacteria and archaea which is usually the outermost layer of the cell. The S layer encloses the entire cell surface and consists of a repeating pattern of protein or glycoprotein subunits.
a narrow extension of a bacterial cell including the plasma membrane and cell wall. Prosthecae can also be short and conical, branched or unbranched, or involved in reproduction.

Not to be confused with S-layer. A layer of diffuse secretions which may adhere loosely to the cell surface. Slime layers mostly consist of unorganized polysaccharide lying outside the bacterial cell wall.

The lysis of erythrocytes. Haemolysis is often detected by growing microorganisms on agar with added erythrocytes (see blood agar). There are several types of heamolytic reactions which can occur (see α-haemolysis, β-haemolysis, γ-haemolysis).
A type of haemolysis which is identifiable by the formation of a zone of opaque green around colonies of an organism when grown on blood agar. This reaction signifies partial lysis of erythrocytes.

A type of haemolysis which is identifiable by the formation of a differentiated zone of clearing (colorless zone) around colonies of an organism when grown on blood agar. This reaction signifies total lysis of erythrocytes.
Pertaining to a reaction observed on blood agar. The formation of a opaque green zone around colonies. synonymous to α-heamolysis.
Any agar based growth medium containing blood.
Of or causing the hydrolysis of carbohydrates.
Greek, from khēmeia and French, from taxonomie
Taxonomy which is based upon comparative analysis of the biochemical composition of organisms (such as 16s RNA structure, DNA base ratio, cell wall lipid content, etc.)
The science of biological classification and the grouping of organisms based upon their similarities. Taxonomy consists of three parts: identification, classification, and nomenclature.
A polyamine which is present in almost all prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells. [NH2(CH2)3NH(CH2)4NH(CH2)3NH2]
A polyamine which is present in almost all prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells. [H2N(CH2)4NH(CH2)3NH2]
A polyamine which is present in almost all prokaryotic and eukaryotic cells. [NH2(CH2)4NH2]
[TeO32−]. An ion which is inhibitory to some bacteria. Tellurite is added to growth media to select for resistant bacteria (Corynebacteria for example).
A test used to determine if an organism is able to grow in the presence of cyanide (usually KCN).

Any microorganism capable of methanogenesis. All known methanogens are archaea and are generally strict anaerobes. Methanogens are common in mud and wetland habitats and in the digestive tracts of ruminants and humans. Many methanogens only growth with simple substrates such as CO2/H2, acetate, methanol, and methylamines.
The formation of methane (CH4) which is carried out as an end product of an energy yielding process by certain archaea.
Any microorganism capable of methanotrophy. That is to say, any microorganism capable of methane as a sole source of carbon and energy.
The use of methane as a sole source of carbon and energy. Not to be confused with methylotrophy which referes to use of any one carbon compound as a sole carbon and energy source.
Any microorganism capable of methylotrophy. That is to say, any microorganism capable of using one carbon compounds as a sole source of carbon and energy.
The use of one carbon compounds as a sole source of carbon and energy. Not to be confused with methanotrophy which is a type of methylotrophy (see methanotrophy).

An enzyme which hydrolyses the (1→4)-β-linkages between N-acetylmuramic acid and N-acetylglucosamine in peptidoglycan. Lysozyme can therefore cause lysis of cells whose peptidoglycan is accessible to enzyme action. Lysozyme is found in the secretions of animals and in certain plants.
Polyene pigments found in members of the Cytophagales. Flexirubin type pigments are the main pigment found in members of the genus Flexibacter.
A bifunctional enzyme which catalyzes the first major step of the Calvin cycle (carbon fixation). RuBisCO is estimated to be the most abundant enzyme on earth.
The full name of the enzyme RuBisCo

A broad term used to describe any organism which has complex nutritional requirements. Often used to refer to organisms which can only be cultured if complex nutrients (such as yeast extract, blood, vitamins, etc.) are added to culture media.
Any fermentation in which there is only one major end product.
Any fermentation in which there is more than one major end product.
denoting a geometric isomer having a pair of identical atoms or groups attached on the same side of two atoms linked by a double bond.
denoting a geometric isomer having a pair of identical atoms or groups on the opposite sides of two atoms linked by a double bond.
a prefix  that can be used in many different situations to mean transverse, across, or beyond.
a prefix  that can be used in many different situations to mean on the near side of, or same side.

See Propamidine isetionate
A term which can be used to describe the shape of a cell, colony, or other morphological feature.
Cell shape: see coccus.
Cell shape: see filamentous

a rigid spiral shaped cell. Spirillum cells are often a long rod or filament shape (length much greater than width) which is spiraled into a repeated waveform. Not to be confused with the "spirochete" morphology which is comprised of flexible spiral shapes. Not to be confused with "Spirillum" (representing the taxon).

a flexible spiral shaped cell with periplasmic flagella. Spirochete cells are often a long rod or filament shape (length much greater than width) which is spiraled into a repeated waveform. Not to be confused with the "spirillum" morphology which is comprised of rigid spiral shapes. Not to be confused with "Spirochaete" or "Spirochete" (representing the taxon).
An uncommon cellular morphology. Cells which exhibit a square or cubical shape. Example Haloquadratum Walsbyi
Pertaining to an arrangement of cocci. Cocci arranged in a 2x2x2 cube (8 cells total). Larger arrangements are also possible (4x4x4). Not to be confused with "Sarcina" representing the taxon.

An acid-fast stain in which a heat fixed smear is flooded with carbolfuchsin and then heated and rinsed in water. The slide is then decolorized with acid-alcohol (HCl in ethanol for example), rinsed, counterstained (with malachite green for example), rinsed and dried.
A diazo dye used as a pH indicator which is blue below pH 3.0 and red above pH 4.5. Congo red also has a high affinity for beta-linked fibrillar polysaccharides and can therefore be used as a stain.
A diazo dye used for stainging intracellular lipids.
Motility produced by the rotation of one or more flagella. See random-walk
indicating several or many, more than one.
Greek,  from hypér + thermós & Latin, from philus
An extremely heat loving organism. An organism whose optimal growth temperature is between 80 to 110 degrees Celsius. Organisms in this group normally can not grow below sixty degrees Celsius.
Used to describe an organism which grows in or tolerates only a narrow temperature range. Compare to "eurythermal".
Used to describe an organism which grows in or tolerates a wide range of  temperatures. Compare to "stenothermal".
Greek, from an, āer & bíos. Latin, from respīrātiōn
Respiration that occurs in anaerobic conditions. That is to say, respiration where the terminal electron acceptor is not oxygen.
A zone of lysis or cell inhibition caused by virus infection on a lawn of bacterial cells.
dental plaque
Medieval Latin, from dentālis & Middle Dutch, from placken
A thin biofilm which forms on the surfaces of teeth consisting of a mixed microbial flora embedded in a matrix composed largely of extracellular polysaccharides.

A small glass test tube open at one end that is used to detect gas production by microbes in liquid culture. A Durham tube is placed inverted within a test tube that is filled with liquid media, and the apparatus is then autoclaved (this drives all air from the Durham tube). After the media is inoculated and incubated any gas formed by the cultured microbes will be trapped within the Durham tube.

Any organism which lives within the tissue or cells of another organism in a symbiotic association. Many cases are obligate endosymbionts; that is to say, the endosymbiont, the host, or both can not survive without the other.
A parasite or endosymbiont which lives within a plant for part or all of its life.
Any or all bacteria normally found in the intestinal tract.
Latin, from inclūsiōn & Old English, from bodig
discrete structures of various types present within the cytoplasmic matrix of cells.
See disc diffusion.
Greek, from mīkro + bíos & Late Latin, from matta
A structure of layered microrganisms which develops on surfaceses in aquatic environments.
Any organism which can grow in an environment which offers very low levels of nutrient.
Any organism which grows only in the presence of high concentration of nutrients.
Two different organisms which live in close physical association.
Archaic: two different organisms which live in close association to their mutual benefit (see mutualism).
One of the participants in a symbiotic relationship.
Symbiosis in which both symbionts derive benefit from the association. Sometimes used to refer to an association between two organisms which cannot live independently.
Symbiosis in which one symbiont derives benefit from the association while the other is not affected (no benefit or harm).
A chemical entity which accepts electrons transferred to it from another compound. An oxidizing agent which, by accepting electrons, is reduced in the process.
Symbiosis in which one symbiont is harmed from the association while the other is not affected (no benefit or harm).
Symbiosis in which one symbiont derives benefit from the association while the other is harmed.
Inhibition of one entity by another similar entity.
Like a ropy, viscous liquid in appearance or consistency.
A gene which encodes the RecA protein.
Not to be confused with RecA (non italic and capital "R") which denotes the protein.
A protein which plays an essential role in the repair and maintenance of DNA.
Not to be confused with recA (italic and lowercase "r") which denotes the gene.
Greek, combining form of eús and gónos
refers to a strain which produces more luxuriant growth on artificial media than that produced by other strains.
Greek, combining form of dys and gónos
refers to a strain which produces poor growth on artificial media when compared to that produced by other strains.
